properties.sfomuseum:description: Interview conducted by Carol L. Osbourne on September 27, 1997.This interview describes Captain Andersen’s experiences as co-pilot, pilot, assistant chief pilot, and chief pilot with Pan American World Airways from 1942 to 1981; his training and role as an instructor in the Civilian Pilot Training program (CPT), at the Tex Rankin School of Aeronautics, and with Pan American; flying out of Seaplane Harbor at Treasure Island from 1944-1946; the move to San Francisco’s Coast Guard Station, then Mills Field (San Francisco Municipal Airport); opening of the new terminal at San Francisco International in 1954 and the growth of the airport since then; the aircraft he flew: training on the Piper Cub, the Ryan ST, and the Fairchild M-62, Martin PBM, Consolidated PB2Y-3, Martin M-130 (China Clipper); the Boeing 314, 377 Stratocruiser, 707, and 747; and the Douglas DC-3, DC-4, and DC-7; Pacific Division routes from San Francisco to Hawaii, Wake Island, Tokyo, Sydney, Auckland, and Fiji; Latin America Division routes from Miami to Rio de Janeiro and Rio to Buenos Aires and Belem; experiences flying soldiers back to the United States during the Korean Airlift 1951-1953; pilot on the first DC-4 polar flight from San Francisco to London in 1957; role as a pilot-manager; reorganizations he experienced; briefly discussion about the mandatory retirement age; memories of San Francisco-based Pan American employees, including Harold Gray, James (Jim) Fleming, Birgit Birkland, Sam Pryor, and Charles (Chuck) Gregg.
